    • Exodos
    • **
    • Unknown if Homer was one person or multiple
      • May have inserted himself into his works as a type of self-portrait
    • The Illiad
      • Exists within 900 year space- most likely originally transcribed from oral history
    • Transcribed approx 1 century after conception
    • 16,000 lines long and composed 10 years before war between the Greeks and the Trojans.
      • The Trojan war
      • This war took place approx 4 years before the piece was written
      • We start in the middle of the war
    • Talks of the flood-almost like in Gilgamesh
      • Couple spared in the flood and tasked with repopulating the earth through throwing stones (the bones of the earth)
    • Troy is the western coast of Turkey
      • Several layers have been excavated in this region discovering cities (9)
      • Some evidence of war in this region from excavations
      • The Hittite kingdom was located near the East of the Troy - can easily make cultural references/connection
    • The Trojan war is started by the Judgement of Paris in which he chooses Aphrodite for love over two other Goddesses, Athena and Hera/ Paris seduced Helen, wife of Spartan Lord Menelaus. Menelaus seeks the aid of his brother Agamemnon.
      • The content of the poem centers around Achilles, the greatest warrior of Agamemnon’s forces
    • Angered the god Apollo by kidnapping Chryseis- the daughter of the high priest Chryses
    • Forced to give up this woman, Agamemnon takes Achilles concubine Briseis in return, angering Achilles and provoking the warrior to “sit out” the war. He will return
    • Achilles is accidentally killed
      • Tension in this poem is that of the immortality of the gods and the mortality of the humans
    • Achilles must reconcile himself to his own mortality
    • Gods have to recognize just how much they’ve become- involved and immersed in human activity
      • Gilgamesh and the Iliad have many similarities
      • The Trojan horse
    • The Odyssey
      • Multiple narratorial perspectives, Odysseus tells his story in the first person in the middle.
      • Dactylic Hexameter is a line of poetry with six metrical feet (one strong stress and two weak stresses)
      • Major spaces: The main hall of Odyseeus kingdom
    • Coming of age, growing old
    • The collateral of war
    • Wit and intellect over sheer fore
    • Arbitrary acts of the gods and the powerlessness of humanity

    The Odyssey#

    Books 1-8#

    • We start with summary of the whole: “He came to see / many people’s cities, where he learned their customs, / while on the sea his spirit suffered many torments” (1.3-5)]
      • Almost like a muse
    • We begin with an assembly of the gods, with Zeus and Athena speaking (Athena loves Odysseus for his cunning and his battle prowess) Zeus: “How could I forget godlike Odysseus, / pre-eminent among all mortal men for his intelligence and offerings / to the mortal gods” (1.66-68)
    • Some linkage to the Illiad
    • The gods will send Hermes, the messenger god, to Calypso, who holds Odysseus on her island (he’s been there seven years) Athena goes to Ithaca, to Odysseus’ palace where his son, Telemachus must entertain suitors to his mother (vying for her hand in marriage with Odysseus gone so long and presumed dead). Note the **hospitality **of Telemachus to the disguised goddess; hospitality is a significant theme in this text, so obsessed with feasting! Notice the contrast between Telemachus and the suitors. Notice too how the bard Phemius performs a song of Achaeans returning from Troy (but Penelope stops him from singing that “painful song” (1.276).
      • Odysseus is a poor young man
      • Hospitality is a central theme of the text and the culture as a whole
    • The idea that when aiding a stranger, you actually might be aiding a god or gods in disguise- you may be rewarded for your actions- so be kind
    • Telemachus is angry with all the suitors- Athena advises Telemachus to sail off and seek the word of his father (King Nestor in Pylos and the to Menelaus in Sparta)
      • ““If you think it’s better and would prefer / that one man’s livelihood should be consumed / without paying anything, I’ll call on / the immortal gods to see if mighty Zeus / will bring about an act of retribution” (1.319-23)”
      • “Telemachus spoke, then threw the scepter on the ground / and burst out crying” (2.52-53).
      • Wily Penelope quote about the suitors- sounds similar to her husband Odysseus
    • “you [suitors] must wait, / although you are keen for me to marry, / till I complete this cloak—for if I don’t, / my weaving would be wasted and in vain” (2.74-77) [but, after four years, she is betrayed by one of her women]
    • Female characters are shown throughout the text weaving (including Athena)- a metaphor for how the narrative of the story is being shaped and spun over time
    • Betrayed by a female servant who thus ends her resistance to the suitors (cant stop them)
    • Athena roams Ithaca in disguise as Telemachus to recruit sailors for him in order to ensure that he is able to depart in a swift manner
      • In Book 3 (omitted from your books), Telemachus will sail to Peleponnese (southern Greece) and journey by land to the city of Pylos where he will be entertained by his father’s old comrade, King Nestor. The King offers his own account of the battles at Troy and his return home to Pylos. The King will send Telemachus on, further, to Sparta to see Menelaus. Nestor’s son, Pisistratus (same name as later Athenian ruler) will accompany Telemachus.
    • Telemachus compares the Hall of Menelaus to Zeus’s kingdom- and is corrected by Minnelaus:
      • “No man alive could rival Zeus, dear boys, / with his everlasting palace and possessions” (4.87-88).
    • Meleanus grieves for Odyseus and recognizes Telemachus by his resemblance to his father
      • Helen’s and Menelaus’ account of Odysseus sneaking into Troy as a beggar and, then, the Trojan Horse: “We heard you [Helen] call. / Two of us—Diomedes and myself—were eager to get up and charge outside / or else to answer back from where we sat, in side the horse. But Odysseus stopped us—/we wished to speak, but he held us in check” (4.86-90)
      • Helen admits that she might have been drugged in Troy
      • We are reminded of the characters own mortality
    • Athena appeals to the gods to aid Odysseus, who is still trapped on the island with Calypso and has been for 7 years. Athena describes the ambush that is being set for Telemachus. Hermes goes to Calypso to tell her that Odysseus must leave the island. Further establishes the theme of mortality vs immortality

      • Odysseus sits regularly by the sea “his eyes always full of tears / because he was squandering his sweet life, mourning / for his return” (5.100-103).

      • Odysseus is Desperate for immortality

    • Monsters stand at the threshold of becoming
      • “Monsters ask us how we perceive our world and “how we have misrepresented what we have attempted to place.”
      • Odysseus starts to embrace his humanity and mortality
    • Odysseus has to leave the island and must build his own boat in order to leave it
      • Reminded of what it means to be a mortal in the realm of the gods
      • However, Poseidon (Sea god) makes his journey difficult and Odysseus ends up washed up on the the shores of Paheacia
    • “Here’s trouble! In this country I have reached, what are the people like? Are they violent and untamed, without a sense of justice? Or are they kind to strangers? In their minds do they fear the gods?”
    • Book 7: Odysseus appears with the queen of the Phoenicians, Arete, and her husband King Alcinous
      • Oyssedeus asks for kindness from the queen
      • Another example of hospitality and sanctuary
      • Alcinous: “If he’s a deathless one come down from heaven, / then gods are planning something different. / So far they’ve always shown themselves to us / in their true form” (7.78-80)
    • They think that Ossyedus may have been sent from the gods
    • However, Odysseus explains that he is mortal and not a god
      • “I’m like mortal men. Indeed, I could recount a longer story, all those hardships I have had to suffer.” (To Alcinous)
      • “After they enjoyed their heart’s fill of food and drink, the minstrel Demodocus, inspired by the Muse, sang about the glorious deeds of warriors, that story, whose fame had climbed to spacious heaven, about Odysseus and Achilles, son of Peleus, when, at a lavish feat in honor of the gods, they fought each other in ferocious argument” (8.34-40)
    • Get a glimpse into the Greek Culture
      • Another feast occurs between Aphrodite and and Ares which Hephaestus (Vulcan) learns about and is embarrassed and angry
    • ““Nasty deeds don’t pay. / The slow one overtakes the swift just as / Hephaestus, slow as he is, has caught Ares, / although of all gods who hold Olympus / he’s the fastest one there is. Yes, he’s lame, / but he’s a crafty one” (124-29).
      • The tortoise and the hare type of situation
    • “He sang about the various ways those warriors / laid waste that lofty town [Troy] and how Odysseus, / like Ares, god of war, and noble Menelaus / went to the home of Deiphobus [Trojan prince], where, he said / Odysseus battled in the most horrendous fight, / from which he then emerged at last victorious” (8.249-54)
    • Omitted text from my edition:
      • “That was the song the famous harper sang / but great Odysseus melted into tears, / … / as a woman weeps, her arms flung around her darling husband, / a man who fell in battle, fighting for town and townsman, / trying to beat the day of doom from home and children. / Seeing the man go down, dying, gasping for breath, / she clings for dear life, screams and shrills—/ but the victors, just behind her, / digging spear-butts into her back and shoulders, / drag her off in bondage, yoked to hard labor, pain, / and the most heartbreaking torment wastes her cheeks. / So from Odysseus’ eyes ran tears of heartbreak now.”
    • Oyssedus ponders his actions, killing,etc.
    • Book 9: Odysseus becomes the bard and the storyteller
      • “now I’ll speak / of the unhappy journey back which Zeus / arranged for me when I returned from war” (9.29-30)
      • The Cicones (failure of his men to find moderation in their savagery and drunkenness)
    • After leaving Troy, Odysseus and her men aim to get more spoils and more goods and material wealth in order to take home
      • Heading to Immarus
      • Plundering artifacts from countries
      • Countries fight against Odysseus
    • Crew ends up off course and in the land of the Lotus-eaters
      • They manage to get away unharmed
      • Questions:
    • What does it mean to remember?
    • What does it mean to forget?
    • What is necessary to keep/lose?
    • Questions of history and its making
      • History has many flows
    • Crew then ends up in the land of the Cyclopes- Takes 12 companions to seek hospitality from the locals who lead them to a cave where Polyphemus live
      • “No man”
    • Tricks the other cyclops
      • “From the cave mighty Polyphemus roared: ‘Nobody is killing me, my friends, / by treachery, not using any force”’ (9.403-4). “He stretched out his arms, / attempting to catch anyone who tried / to escape there with the sheep” (9.415-17).”
      • Polyphemus kills 2 of the men and eats them
      • In order to escape, they must have Polyphemus open the door to the cave so that they can escape
    • Get him drunk- They blind him with a stick and he is therefore unable to find Odysseus
      • Odysseus abuses verbally the Polyphemus (Poseidon’s son)- makes Poseidon hate Odysseus
    • The cyclops; “They don’t grow / any plants by hand or plough the earth, / but put their trust in the immortal gods, / and though they never sow or work the land, / still every kind of crop springs up for them” (9.92-96).
    • “Each one of them / sets out laws for his own wives and children, / and they shun all dealings with each other” (9.101-103). “He avoided others / and lived alone, away from all the rest, / a law unto himself, a monster, made to be a thing of wonder, not like a man, / who survives by eating bread, no, more like / a soaring wooded mountain standing there / to view in isolation from the rest” (9.145-51 ).
    • “l told the rest of my trustworthy crew / to stay there beside the ship and guard it, / while I selected twelve of my best men / and went off to explore. I took with me / a goatskin full of dark sweet wine” (9.152-55). “l was keen / to see the man in person and find out / if he would show me hospitality (9.180-82). “We’re here / as suppliants to you, and Zeus protects / all suppliants and strangers—as god of guests, / he cares for all respected visitors” (9.218-21 ).
      • Another example of the theme of hospitality
        • Men are brash to assume that the host will agree to their indulgence
    • Odysseus escaped through hanging onto the bottom of the sheep
    • Another instance of Odysseus being mortal, cannot compete with the might of a god such as Poseidon
    • Odysseus travels to Aeolia
      • Aeolus gives Odysseus a bag of ox hide
    • Unknown why he did this
    • In reality this is the “bag of winds”
    • They can see Ithaca- Odysseus falls asleep
      • The others on the boat open the sack in order to see what is in it (they seemed to believe that it was treasure)
      • The winds and seas push the boat back to Aeolia
    • King is furious- no lenience
      • “Of all living mortals, you are the worst— so you must leave this island with all speed. It would violate all sense of what is right if I helped out or guided on his way a man the blessed gods must hate. So leave. You’re here because the deathless gods despise you.”
      • “Once they heard his [Antiphates] call, / the mighty Laestrygonians poured out, / thronging in countless numbers from all sides—/ not like men at all, but Giants” (131-34).
      • They encounter man-eating giants called Laestrygonians
    • Trapped the 12 ships- only Odysseus ship escaped
      • They then encounter Circe and her island-turns a party of men into pigs- one escapes to warn the others
    • Hermes gives him the antidote to Circe’s powers- makes Circe vow not to plot or take revenge against his crew. The Pigs are then turned back into men
    • “Inside their pens they wept. / Circe threw down some feed in front of them— / acorns, beech nuts, and cornel fruit—the stuff / pigs eat when they are wallowing in mud” (10.217-220).
    • “Take a remedial medicine with you, / and go to Circe’s house. It will protect you” (10.239-40).
    • “l found my trusty comrades at the ship / lamenting sadly, shedding many tears. / Just as on farms calves frisk around the herd / when cows, having had their fill of grazing, / return back to the yard—they skip ahead, / and pens no longer hold them, as they run, / mooing in a crowd around their mothers, / that’s how my companions, once they saw me, / thronged around” (378-83)
    • Odysseus and crew go to the shores of the underworld
      • Perform a sacrifice which brings the spirits of the dead to drink the blood
    • Also includes Odysseus aunt Claire

      • The Prophet Tiresias comes with the spirits
    • Tiresias offers a grim future for Odysseus: “a god will make your journey bitter” (11.66) but he offers some hope and a warning: “If you leave [the cattle and rich flocks of Helios the sun god] unharmed and keep your mind / on your return, you may reach Ithaca” (71-72). Further, he tells Odysseus: “There’ll be trouble at home—insolent men / eating up your livelihood and wooing / your godlike wife by giving courtship gifts” (11 . 79-81 ). “Your death will come / out of the sea, such a gentle passing, / when you are bowed down with a ripe old age, / and your people prospering around you” (100-3).
      • Another relationship between the mortal and the immortal
      • “Odysseus sees a procession of military heroes and women including Ajax, Agamemnon, and Epicaste (Jocasta), the wife/mother of Oedipus. He sees other mythological figures like Tantalus and Sisyphus. Most significant, he meets Achilles.”
      • “Before now, / while you were still alive, we Achaeans / honored you as we did the gods. And now, / since you’ve come down here, you rule with power / among those who have died. So Achilles, / you have no cause to grieve because you’re dead” (11.330-35).
      • Achilles responds: Don’t try to comfort me about my death, / glorious Odysseus. I’d rather live . working as a wage-laborer for hire / by some other ma, one who had not land / and not much livelihood, than lord it over all the waster dead” (11.337-42)
    • Circe warns the returned Odysseus of his next obstacles, the sirens and later, the Scylla and Charybdis. Then will arrive at Helio’s island, Thrinacia, where he’ll find the cattle and sheep not meant to be interfered with.
      • The Sirens: “No man has ever rowed his black ship / past here without attending to our songs, / sweet-voiced melodies sung from our own lips. / That brings him joy, and he then goes away / a wiser man, for we two understand / all the misfortunes faced by Trojans and Achaeans” (12.154-60).
      • Must also make it past the 6 headed Hydra
      • To prevent the men from hearing the sirens and falling victim to them, beeswax is put into the men’s ears
      • Scylla and Charybdis: “l did not mention Scylla—for she was / a threat for which there was no remedy—in case my comrades, overcome with fear, / stopped rowing and huddled up together / inside the boat” (12.191-95).
      • “When we saw Charybdis, we were afraid / we’d be destroyed. Then Scylla snatched away / six of my companions, right from the ship / … / They cried and screamed, calling me by name / on final time, their hearts in agony” (12.209-11 , 216-17).
    • Lost six of the men on the boat to the Hydra
      • Men are tired and do not want to continue on, and despite Odysseus not agreeing, land the ship on the island of Thrinacia
    • At Thrinacia, observing Helios’ cattle and sheep: “Shipmates, / let all of you now swear this solemn oath— / if by chance we find a herd of cattle / or a large flock of sheep, not one of you / will be so overcome with foolishness / that you will kill a cow or sheep” (12.237-42). “Once what we had stored / inside our ship was gone, they had to roam, / scouring around for game and fish and birds, / whatever came to hand” (12. 270-73). “The gods / immediately sent my men bad omens— / hides crept along the ground, while on the spits / the meat began to bellow, and a sound / like cattle lowing filled the air” (12.358-62)
    • Helios takes his revenge, conjures a storm that wipes out all of the crew on the deck of the ship. Odysseus escapes by taking hold of a branch of a tree above the whirlpool swallowing the ship
    • Reprisals: “All at once, West Wind whipped up / a frantic storm—the blasts of wind snapped off / both forestays on the mast, which then fell back, / … / In the stern part of the ship, the falling mast / struck the helmsman on his head, caving in / his skull, every bone at once. Then he fell, / like a diver, off the boat. His proud spirit / left his bones. Then Zeus roared out his thunder / and with a bolt of lightning struck our ship. / The blow from Zeus’s lightning made our craft / shiver from stem to stern and filled it up / with sulphur smoke. My men fell overboard / and rode atop the waves” (12.375-88).
    • I was guided to Ogygia by the gods, / the island where fair-haired Calypso live” (12.420-21).

      • Does not initially recognize his homeland

Ithaca is well known, even in Troy, / a long way from Achaean land, they say” (13.80-85). “I’ll tell you what Fate has in store for you. / You’ll find harsh troubles in your well-built home. / Be patient, for you must endure them all” (104-6).
      • “she touched him with her staff. / She wrinkled the lovely skin on his supple limbs / and took the dark hair from his head” (13.152-54)

So describe / the style of clothing he was wearing” (19.56-59).

    • Book 21:
      • Bk 21: the contest with bow and axes: Penelope: “So come now, suitors, since I seem to be / the prize you seek, I’ll place this great bow here— / a weapon that belonged to great Odysseus. / Whichever one of you can grip this bow and string it with the greatest ease, then shoot / an arrow through twelve axes, all of them, / I’ll go with him, leaving my married home, / this truly lovely house and all these goods / one needs for living—things I’ll remember, / even in my dreams” (21 .16-26). “If Odysseus were to come back suddenly, / … would you two / be the sort of men who would defend him?” (21.104-5).
      • Reckoning with the suitors
      • String bow and shoot through axes
    • None of the suitors can do it
    • Suitors decide to give up and try again tomorrow
      • Reveals himself to Eumaeus and Philoetius
      • Odysseus strings the bow easily and shoots through the 12 axe heads
      • Antinous, i his cowardice, having seen Eurymachus fail at the bow, urges them all to put this aside and feast some more: “At this moment, / in this country there’s a feast day, sacred / to the god. So who would bend the bow! No, / set it aside without saying a thing” (21.173-76). But Odysseus steps forwards and ask for a chance with the weapon. He is mocked but Penelope insists.
    • Book 22
      • “Shrewd Odysseus, / once he’d lifted up the bow and looked it over / from every angle, then—just as someone truly skilled / at playing the lyre and singing has no trouble / when he loops a taut string around a brand new peg, / tying the twisted sheep’s gut down at either end—/ that’s how easily lord Odysseus strung that bow” (21.254-60).
      • “This contest to determine who is best / is over. But there’s another target— / one no man has ever struck—I’ll find out / if I can hit it. May Apollo grant / I get the glory” (22. 5-9)

    • Osydeus and the others are protected from the arrows and the other suitors trying to kill him
    • Book 23
      • “Wake up now, Penelope, my dear child, so you yourself can see with your own eyes what you’ve been wanting each and every day. Odysseus has arrived. He may be late, but he’s back in the house. And he’s just killed those haughty suitors who upset this home, used up his goods, and victimized his son.”
      • Ossedyus knows that he has created danger due to the killing of the large number of suitors
      • Odysseus and Penlope reunite
      • “Strange man, / I am not making too much of myself, / or ignoring you.         Oedipus Tyrannos

    • Important context events:
      • Sophocles (495-406 BCE)
    • Most successful playwright of the 5th century of the BCE
    • Appointed was appointed as one of ten counselors to guide Athens after the military disasters in 413
      • Golden Age of Athenian Democracy collapses after the death of Pericles in 429
      • Political Infighting, Mob Rule, Plague- 420s
      • Polyponnesian War with Sparta (431-404 BCE)
      • Oedipus Tyrannos was performed initially between 428-25 BCE in the middle of a second outbreak of plague in the city
    • Context of the plays content meant for an audience confronting the existential crises of political upheaval
    • Casts were all male and they wore oversized masks to emphasize the mood of the character that they are portraying
      • Theater built to honor Dionysus
    • Acoustic design
    • Athenian Art and Philosophy
      • Herodotus, Aeschylus, Sophocles
      • 4th century thinkers emerge after Polyponesian war
      • Alexander the Great
    • Keywords
      • Ruin
      • Sight and Blindness
      • Prophecy
    • The Oedipus story was known to the audience before they even arrived at the theater to watch Sophocles’ play. Oedipus is mentioned in Homer’s Iliad Epicaste (Jocasta) is visited by Odysseus in Homer’s Odyssey in 467 BCE, Aeschylus presented a trilogy on Oedipus’ family (a play on Laius, one on Oedipus, and the Seven Against Thebes (which survives today)
